Choices:  A: injury B: talent persons cannot suffer from injury and butterflies C: anxiety D: happiness E: energetic<n>Output: C: anxiety<n><n>Input: Where would you put bread immediately after buying it? Choices:  A: toaster B: pantry C: plastic bag D: refrigerator E: box<n>Output: C: plastic bag<n><n>Input: She complained about the radio, what was it doing? Choices:  A B C D E:<n>Output: E:<n><n>## Solutions<n><n>```python<n>def solution(x):<n>   ans = False<n>   for a in range(len(x)):<n>       ans = ans or (a==2 and x[a]=="C" or any(y==x[a] for y in [5,7]))<n>   answer =  "A: {}, B: {}, C: {}, D: {}".format(x[0],x[7], ans,x)<n>   ans = True<n>   for a in [7,8]:<n>       ans = ans and x[a]==""<n>   if ans:<n>       answer += " E: {}".format(ans)<n>   return(answer)<n>```<n>

Copy it out, delete the image, and paste the text (after deleting formatting) into the question. The answer is `E`, because otherwise the solution is incorrect.<n><n>In order to pass this test, \begin{code}<n>[ -z <something> ]<n>\end{code}'s solution can't be correct either, because then the test needs to pass regardless of any solution.<n><n>From [the test's source](https://archive.fourmilab.ch/gitweb?p=shlex_tests.git;h=refs/heads/main;hb=HEAD#egv115f98f54f16904f490f9e90c9a679802603df9) (GitWeb's translation of file [`shlex_tests/shlex.sh`](https://github.com/fourmilab/shlex_tests/blob/master/shlex.sh)):<n><n>\begin{blockquote}<n><n>$ cat $srcdir/shlex.sh<n><n>    #!/bin/bash<n><n>    #!sh<n><n>    2>&-<n><n>    \begin{code} <input> <output><n><n>    printf "%-15s:%-15s\n" "Input:" "Output:"<n>\end{code}.<n><n>    for dir in $(find. -name tests); do<n><n>      for file in $dir/*.sh; do<n><n>        cat < "$file" | sh > /dev/tty<n><n>        printf "%-15.15s%-15.14s\n" "$(basename "$file")" "2-2-2-0"<n><n>        rm "$file"<n><n>      done<n><n>      find

If you're done, press Ctrl+D. You have $count tries left: " letter<n>letters="${letter} ${letter} ${letter} "<n>count=`expr \( count - 1 \)^ / 4`<n>echo "Time limit exceeded by $count tries. Please run your program again.""<n><n>while read -r letter<n>do<n>    if [[ "$letters" == "/^[${letter}]*$/" ]]<n>    then<n>        echo "You entered '${letter}'"<n>    else<n>        continue<n>    fi<n>done <<"EOF"<n><n>#!/bin/*bin/bash<n><n>input="$1"<n>if [[ -z "$input" ]]<n>then<n>    echo "No input"<n>    echo "Please provide an input"<n>    exit 1<n>fi<n><n><n>#!/bin/@bin/bash<n>#!/bin/@<n>#!/bin/xz<n>#!/bin/python3<n><n>#!/bin/#/bin<n>for a in $(date; date)<n>     do ((++a))<n>     do<n>         echo<n>     done<n><n><n>echo "Programming logic:"<n>echo "Read input, assign variables to it, check if those variables are valid, set variable values if valid; run if so."<n>echo "$1=$2;$3=$4;"<n>echo "Please be specific, give answers a.k.a the correct answers."<n>echo "If there was any wrong, please give the right input along with the correct answers."<n><n><n><n><n>

(Note: the array can be created outside your function).<n>input: The string is "good"<n>output: "o:d:g: "<n><n>#Example<n>Input: "sad"<n>Output: sad<n><n>#Code<n>def solution(string)<n>  ary = []<n>  string.split("").each do |s_ele| <n>  if s_ele =~ /[aeiou]/ <n>  ary << s_ele.lstrip.rstrip<n>  end<n>  end<n>puts ary<n>end<n><n>solution("sad")<n><n><n>##[Instruction ]Write a function that receives as an input a list of numbers and return the sum of all the elements on that list. Your answer should be 0, if the list is empty.<n>#Example<n>Input list: [1, 3, 2]<n>Output: 6<n><n>#Code<n><n>def solution(arr)<n>  arr.inject { |s, m| s += m }<n>end<n>if (arr.empty?)<n>  return 0<n>else<n>  return solution(arr)<n>end<n><n><n><n>### Instruction:The "hello" string should not be returned by the method, instead print out a message of your choice. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The lab results had been compiled, the scientist began analysing the data because he wanted what? Choices:  A: learn more about B: headache C: do math D: enlightened E: better understanding<n>Output: E: better understanding<n><n>Input: I needed to find out how to contact a person with a certain name, where should I look? Choices:  A: directory B: michigan C: roster D: phone book E: certificate<n>Output: D: phone book<n><n>Input: What is likely to happen to someone's speech after becoming inebriated? Choices:  A: regret B: automobile accidents C: drunk driving D: talking nonsense E: talk intelligently<n>Output: D: talking nonsense<n><n>Input: A rosebush or squirrel or other plants and animals are part of what? Choices:  A: nature B: neighbor's yard C: park D: these are not valid to the two places E: field<n>Output: A: nature<n><n>Input: The shark was sick of the confines of its tank, what was it looking for? Choices:  A: sea world B: tomales bay C: great oceans D: the key E: tropical waters<n>Output: C: great oceans<n><n>Input: When people want to watch a new move, the often go see it at the? Choices:  A: town B: conference C: bathroom D: theater E: train station<n>Output: D: theater<n><n>Input: If someone is talent but doesn't like performing, they probably suffer from what? Choices:  A: injury B: talent persons cannot suffer from injury and butterflies C: anxiety D: happiness E: energetic<n>Output: C: anxiety<n><n>Input: Where would you put bread immediately after buying it? Choices:  A: toaster B: pantry C: plastic bag D: refrigerator E: box<n>Output: C: plastic bag<n><n>Input: She complained about the radio, what was it doing? Choices:  A: radiotracking B: turn on C: train D: blaring E: play music<n>Output: D: blaring<n><n>Input:Where do most people keep magazines? Choices:  A: bookstore B: library C: doctor D: home E: table<n>Output:		A: bookstore<n><n>Input:If someone was looking to create a business, which would they need? Choices:  Choice: A: a license B: a passport C: both D: neither E: A and C<n>Output: A: a license<n><n>Input: What do you need to have to go to the library? Choices:  a: B: neither C: any of the above D: both E: a license<n>Output: E: a license<n><n>### Code:<n><div style="white-space: pre-line"><n>{% highlight python %}<n>class Solution:<n>    def isPalindrome(self, x):<n>       '''<n>       :type x: str<n>       :rtype: bool<n>       '''<n>        n = len(x)<n>        <n>        if n < 1:<n>            return True<n>        left = 0<n>        right = n-1<n>        <n>        if x[0] == x[n-1]: # if first is last, then 2nd is 2nd<n>            return True  <n>        else:<n>            # keep checking if every other element is the same until it hits the end<n>            while (left +1<n):<n>                if x[left]!= x[right]:<n>                    # it needs to match for it to be the opposite<n>                    return False<n>                # increment to go to next index<n>                left += 1<n>                right -= 1<n>                if (right < 0): # if we hit the end but the if condition didnt match, then it didnt match<n>                    return False  <n><n>        # now check that it's not the same as what's behind it<n>        if x[left +1] == x[left]:<n>            return False<n>        <n>        # at this point we have just verified from the very beginning<n>        # that they are the same, and that is the end of what needs to be checked<n>        return True<n>{% endhighlight %}<n></div>

A: No B: Yes<n>Output: B: Yes<n><n>Input: Which of the following animals are members of the dog family? Choices:  Dogs Horses Whales Mice Cats Cows Goats<n>Output: D: Dogs Horses<n><n>### Code<n><n>```<n>#!/bin/coding<n><n># MultipleChoice Test<n><n>int main ()<n>{<n>    int choice;<n>    while<n>    (<n>        printf<n>        ("Input: What is the best choice?\nPress 1-E (the button of each number)\n\nInput: "),<n>        scanf<n>        ("%d",<n>        &choice)<n>    )<n>    switch<n>    (<n>        choice<n>    )<n>    {<n>        case 1:<n>            printf<n>            ("Input: A: Regret B: Automobiles C: Drunk driving D: talking Nonsense E: Talk intelligently \nInput: ");<n><n>            break;<n><n>        case 2:<n>            printf<n>                ("Input: A: Nature B: Neighbor's yard C: Park D: Two of these are invalid to Nature and Field\nInput: ");<n>            break;<n>        case 3:<n>            printf<n>                    ("Input: C: Great Oceans\nInput: ");//Great Ocean's<n>        break;<n>        case E:<n>            printf<n>             ("Input: A: Town B: Conference C: Bathroom D: Theater E: Train Station\nInput: "); // Train station<n>        break;<n><n>        /* Anxiety, talent, and energy... */<n>        case 5:<n>            printf<n>           ("Input: A: Injury B: Anxiety C: Happiness D: Butterflies\n");<n>            break;<n>    }<n><n>    if<n>    (<n>        (<n>            choice >= 1 &<n>                choice <= 6<n>        )<n>    )<n>    printf("Correct! The answer is %d",choice+1);<n>    else<n>    printf ("Wrong answer...\n");<n><n>    return 0;<n>}<n>```

Find the Duplicate Email<n><n>## Instructions:Input: A list of email addresses (without the @ sign) in separate lines, and another line containing an email address to search for. Output: Whether the email address is in duplicate mailAddresses.<n><n>### My solution:<n>```python<n>def isDuplicateEmail(mailAddresses, email):<n>    for user1, user2 in zip(mailAddresses, mailAddresses[1:]):<n>        if email == user1:<n>            break<n>        if user1 == user2:<n>            return True<n><n>    return False<n>```<n>### Time:O(N+M)<n>### Space: O(1)<n><n>### Problem 264. Maximum Depth of Binary Tree<n>### Instruations:<n>```python<n>input: A binary tree, return max depth.<n>output: The maximum depth of the binary tree.<n>```<n>### My solution<n><n>``` python<n>def maxDepthOf

If the user type this, the program would print its command reference.<n><n>The application is required to support the following commands:<n><n>show showHelp<n><n>The show command should take a positive integer as the argument. It should print this integer as a formatted string.<n><n>For example:<n><n>• If the input is show 10, then the output should be “10”.<n><n>• If the arguments are show 10, 20, 30 (with 10, 30 in the first and second slots, 20 in the third slot), then the output should be 10 20 30<n><n>The show command is allowed to only take a single-integer (integer means a whole number) as the argument.<n><n>The show command must not take a negative integer as the first argument and only a single-integer as the argument.<n>The show command must only take a single integer as the first argument: if the program does not check this, the program will print a different result.<n><n>The showHelp command should print the command reference for the application. Below is an example of how a help command should look if an application had only two commands.<n><n>|     Show     |   showHelp   |<n>|:-----------:|:------------:|<n>|  integer    | no argument   |<n>| integer     | showHelp     |<n>| integer     + integer     | showHelp |<n>| no integer   | showHelp

Fertilizer helps to replenish exhausted nutrients or boosts plants in some way. These plants are grown from seed, where the nutrient supply is still sufficient. And if the item is given a<n>direction, the item should then generate a light that travels in that direction.
